roperty regimes. The fact that cumulative destocking (97 animals) exceeds initial herd sizes (90 animals) by year 100 indicates chronic herd depletion requiring external replenishment or restocking mechanisms to maintain viability. The wide variance in outcomes implies that uniform policy interventions may be ineffective; instead, targeted support for high-destocking households and investigation of the factors driving successful low-destocking trajectories (potentially associated with specific learning behaviors) would be warranted. The persistent accumulation even in late years suggests that learning mechanisms and social learning (E-RO-SL1) or learning-by-doing (E-LBD) do not fully eliminate destocking pressure under the modeled climatic variability, indicating need for complementary risk management strategies beyond behavioral adaptation alone."
